The trial of two Sikh immigrants from India, Malik and Bagri, charged with the Air India bombings in 1985, has been complex.
Prosecutors built their case on witness testimonies, phone records, and motives.
Bagri's lawyer claims his innocence, while prosecutors argue they were part of a plot to bomb Air India jets.
Witnesses confessed details of their involvement, and the motive was revenge for India's 1984 attack on the Golden Temple.
The trial, involving 113 witnesses, has been exhaustive, with the prosecution alleging the accused sought to create an independent Sikh state.
